 have been chosen to form the axis for this interpretation of Calvin’s contribution. These texts deal with his theological view of law, a definition of sanctification, and a short treatise on the Christian life. The portrait of Calvin’s spirituality that emerges from these texts and the larger framework of his theology, his ecclesiology, and his career as church leader and civic organizer can be summarized in the following phrase: a practical spirituality of sanctification by participation in society. One cannot find all of that in these texts, but they establish a platform on which the pieces fall into place. The story of his early life and formation, along with several key ideas that characterize the man and his vision, will help to draw a sharper, more distinctive picture of at least this influential aspect of Calvin’s spirituality. It is one that bears direct relevance, with appropriate adjustments, to life today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aReformed ChurchxControversial literature. 0aTheology, Doctrinal. 4aHistory. 4aReligion. 4aTheology. 7aRELIGION / Spirituality.2bisacsh1 aHaight, Roger, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaminski, Amanda Avila, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPach, Alfred, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075168040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781531505769?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781531505769423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781531505769/original  a978-3-11-075168-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles